snippet.textDisplay:
It's funny, all the "details" they're talking about how the deep base got distorted by the sub woofer, the humming and how they got it in there... Stuff that otherwise get's fixed before a produced song goes out. I like it. I remember when I got into recording and mixing and how I ended up doing the same, leaving all those small things in, in the end because I think that recording and mixing today has become so hi def, so easy to manipulate and have such low threshold of getting into that for one, everything is so polished that it easily can get to feel too sterile and secondly every other song from many different artist starts to sound the same, So while when people back in the day recorded on tape and with less hi def equipment a lot of character came from that, so that now when it's digital and super hi quality equipment is relatively cheap, the character of a production and the arrangement of the song have to comes not from those old quirks and artifacts, but from the texture and personality the artist themselves put into it.

I don't do much recording and mixing any more but when I do, I use a simple field recorder with a set of decent built in x/y mics and an old laptop. I't not much, but it get's the job done and to me at least the portability of it all makes it so that my recordings of both other's and myself are always very honest and raw, and filled with personality. Almost like they where recorded live at a party with some friends having fun, just jamming around. Mostly because more often than not they where, with a bit of tinkering afterwards, and some more layers. And that's what so cool with all this new technology we have to day, or at least I think so.
